                                      muKern v.0.1.062026

A small microkernel for x86_64, ARMv8-A and RV64. The kernel itself
provides only three things -- tasks, a scheduler, and synchronous IPC.
Everything else (the serial, VGA and keyboard drivers, the console, the
shell) is an ordinary task that talks over messages. On x86_64 the shell
is a full local console: type on the PS/2 keyboard, see it on the VGA
text screen -- and the very same shell is reachable over the serial line
at the same time.

WHAT MAKES IT A MICROKERNEL

The kernel core (kernel/core/) contains no device code at all. Drivers
are server tasks (kernel/srv/) that own a piece of hardware and answer a
small message protocol (con.h). A client -- the shell -- only ever sends
messages; it has no idea whether its bytes reach a UART, a screen, or a
keyboard:

    shell  --con.h-->  console server  --con.h-->  serial driver  (in+out)
                                       |--con.h-->  vga driver     (out)
                                       \--con.h-->  keyboard driver (in)

Output is fanned to serial and the screen; input is gathered from serial
and the keyboard, whichever types first. The call graph is acyclic, so
the blocking-rendezvous IPC can never deadlock. Scheduling is
cooperative: control follows the message.

Today every task shares one address space and runs privileged; per-task
address spaces, user mode and trap-based syscalls are the next milestone
(see ROADMAP). Even so the *structure* is already a microkernel: the
kernel is policy-free and every driver is a replaceable, scheduled
server reached only by IPC.

BUILD & RUN

Toolchain setup (rootless container) is in INSTALL. Then:

    $ make all              # build all three kernels
    $ make run-x86_64       # boot in QEMU, serial console (-nographic)
    $ make run-arm64
    $ make run-riscv64
    $ make demo-vga         # x86_64 with a real VGA display + serial

Quit QEMU with Ctrl-A then x.

    mukern> help
    commands:
      help          this list
      arch          print architecture
      echo <text>   print text
      ps            list tasks and their states
      clear         clear the screen
      fault         raise a CPU exception (trap demo)
      panic         call panic() directly
      halt          stop the cpu
      exit          terminate the shell task

    mukern> ps
     tid  state      name
       0  ready      idle
       1  dead       init
       2  recv-wait  serial
       3  recv-wait  vga
       4  recv-wait  kbd
       5  recv-wait  console
       6  run        shell  <= self

Every keystroke and every character above is a round trip of IPC
through the console and driver servers. On x86_64 the same output
appears on the VGA screen and the shell accepts input from the PS/2
keyboard as well as the serial line, so `make demo-vga` gives you a
self-contained local console (docs/vga-keyboard-demo.png).

SOURCE LAYOUT

    include/            public interfaces (arch, hal, ipc, task, con, ...)
    kernel/core/        the kernel: tasks, scheduler, ipc, init, shell, panic
    kernel/srv/         driver/console SERVER tasks (serial, vga, kbd, console)
    kernel/lib/         freestanding libc bits + con client + kprintf
    arch/<arch>/        boot, traps, context switch, raw UART/VGA/KBD back-ends

NOTES

Per-arch boot paths and UARTs:

| arch    | boot path                          | UART                 | load addr  |
|---------|------------------------------------|----------------------|------------|
| x86_64  | Multiboot1 to long-mode trampoline | 16550 @ 0x3F8        | 1 MiB      |
| arm64   | QEMU virt ELF entry (EL1)          | PL011 @ 0x9000000    | 0x40080000 |
| riscv64 | OpenSBI to S-mode payload          | NS16550 @ 0x10000000 | 0x80200000 |

The x86_64 kernel is linked as ELF64 then re-wrapped to `elf32-i386`
with `objcopy` so QEMU's Multiboot loader accepts it; the machine code
is unchanged. VGA text mode lives at the identity-mapped 0xB8000.
